{% contentBlock
  'Discovery', 4,
  '<img src="/images/usability-mobile.jpg" alt="Framer Prototype">
  <p class="caption">Fig 4 - The submit activity slip screen on the initial app</p>',
  '<p>After we had a first cut of the software working on our phones. The next phase of the project was to get feedback from our users as to whether it fit their needs as well as understanding what worked and what didn’t. We spoke to one of our customers who had previously indicated that they would like a mobile time tracking solution.</p>
  <p>The interview and usability test revealed that the time tracking process was core to their business, but that there were a lot of inefficiencies to the way they were doing it right now. It involved recording information in a separate place, like a notebook and then spending time on a computer at some time during the week to upload the information to our desktop software. They’ve been long asking for a mobile solution to upload this information. This insight validated the product direction that we were going in.</p>
  <p>I also spent some time with our development team understanding the technology behind React Native and how the code compiles to native iOS & Android components. This information was really useful to the wider design team and I to understanding what kind of components and visual style we could use within the app. This helped me better understand the constraints and what we got out of the box with react native. This helped me understand what cases to handle with the design and to know what would be taken care of.</p>'
%}
{% contentBlock
  'Definition & Design', 6,
  '<p>Collating all the feedback let us make improvements to the existing flow we had. For example, some of the feedback we received indicated that users preferred to enter information in their own way as opposed to entering it in the flow that we made. In order to fix this issue, we changed the order of the flow to allow people to add in information as they liked.</p>
  <p>The conversations we had with our users also allowed us to understand what the key workflows were within the app and to identify other opportunities to build out the app. For example, we began to understand that an equivalent of the app was a diary, where people were recording their work related information.</p>',
  '<img src="/images/updated-flows.png" alt="Updated flows">
  <p class="caption">Fig 5 - An example of how the flows were changed</p>'
%}
{% contentBlock
  'Results', 12,
  '<p>As a result of the work we did in this loop,  we were able to get a version of the app that we felt comfortable in releasing to our first wave of beta testers.</p>
    <p>addition to the workflows we changed as part of the feedback rounds, we spent time setting up the help and feedback portals for the beta process. This helped us later in the process to scale our feedback gathering to improve the product.</p>'
%}
